# Code Quality

- Prefer readable, explicit code over clever code.
- Keep functions focused and reasonably small.
- Avoid duplicated logic; extract helpers when duplication becomes meaningful.
- Add or update tests when behavior changes.
- Do not add dependencies unless necessary.
- If adding a dependency, explain why existing code or standard tooling is insufficient.
- Keep public interfaces stable unless the task explicitly requires a breaking change.
- Prefer typed interfaces where the language supports them.
- Keep generated, build, and formatting-only changes separate from functional changes when practical.
